shared_text:
The Voice of WMU
August 24 at 6:30 PM ¬∑

A few helpful first day of school things for the WMU 6-12 graders:

1. Instead of meeting in the big gym, like usual, we will meet in homerooms (don‚Äôt freak out yet)

2. Tomorrow I will post a list of students and their homerooms. Please check the list. If you are not on the list, please email kathy.mullin@wmucsd.org or rita.williams@wmucsd.org and it will be fixed.

3. If you forget what homeroom you are in, there will be lists posted around the school and all of the teachers will have the lists also. So breathe.

4. If you don‚Äôt know what room you are going to, or recognize the teacher‚Äôs name, we will help you.

5. In your homerooms, you will get schedules (things are still changing a bit), ids, talk about block scheduling, lunches, the return to learn plan, lockers, and all those things.

6. Remember, we will all be in the halls to help you between classes. If you need help at anytime, please ask. It‚Äôs a very different year, but one thing hasn‚Äôt changed, we are excited to see you all!!

#wearewmu #wmucsd #wolvespride

Registration for WMU is open. We mailed direction letters on Friday! It is open for 5 days. If you need assistance, call Rita or I and we can meet you at the red Music door between 9-noon daily. Please complete your registration soon.

Preschool 4 year olds-there are no fees associated with preschool. Students must have all forms in prior to the first day of preschool. Mrs. Sasha Gallagher and Ms. Jill Humiston Townsley will be in contact with you regarding first day of preschool and home visits. (I do know that preschool DOES NOT start on August 24th but I do THINK it starts August 27th however stay tuned for their letter next week.

post_text:
Tonight's softball game NL vs North Mahaska has been moved to North Mahaska. WMU was scheduled to host it.

Taken from New London's fb page:

Tonight's Regional Semi-Final game location has been moved to North Mahaska at 7 PM.

There were several factors that went into the location of this game. Here is a note from the Iowa Girls High School Athletic Union detailing how the decision was made.

"North Mahaska will host New London in the 1A Region 6 Regional Semi on July 17 at 7 p.m. There was no head to head, both teams were 1-1 against common opponents so it came down to overall winning percentage. North Mahaska 10-7 (.588) vs. New London 8-6 (.571)."

Seth Schurr and John Martin will be continuing to collect scrap metal. Jeremiah Schlee will also be now be collecting with us.

The scrap metal collection trailer will no longer be sitting in Dale‚Äôs backyard. The trailer will now be located along West Central Avenue in Winfield, at the northwest corner of the W-MU School Bus lot.

If you have a way to load and haul your metal donations and appliances, please deliver your donations to the trailer.

shared_text:
Brooke McArtor‚ÄéWinfield, IA Events & FOR SALE group
June 8 at 11:44 AM ¬∑

WMU reminder- At the start of the 2017, there were changes made to Iowa immunization laws. Just a reminder that this affects our incoming 7th graders and 12th graders. I will need to have an updated form on file for this.

This change requires that all students entering, advancing or transferring into 7th grade will need proof of one dose of meningococcal conjugate vaccine (MenACWY) and a Tdap (Tetanus, Diphtheria, and Pertussis/whooping cough) booster. All students entering, advancing, or transferring into 12th grade will need proof of two doses of the meningococcal (A, C W, Y) vaccine (or 1 dose if received when the applicant was 16 years of age or older).

Please note that a updated form needs to be turned into WMU prior to August 1st in order to start school. This is a great time to get in for the vaccines while the clinics are still slow! If your insurance allows, Public health is also a good place but don't forget to check their hours in the event of a change for covid.

May 28, 2020

Dear W-MU Students and Parents,

We regret to inform you that the 2020 W-MU Junior-Senior Prom has been canceled. This decision is based on the recommendation of the Director of the Henry County Public Health Department, and taking into account the overall health and safety of our students and staff.

This is a very difficult decision, and one we‚Äôve tried to find safe alternatives and solutions. However we‚Äôve not been able to construct a viable plan or venue where health risks could be mitigated to the degree necessary for our students and staff.

If you have any questions, please contact Supt. Jeff Maeder at 319-257-7700 x101.

post_text: From Kathy Woodsmall Mullin
shared_text:
The Voice of WMU
March 20 at 6:49 PM ¬∑

For 6-12 grade students and parents:

Starting on Monday, teachers will post activities on whatever site they use, Google Classroom or Edmodo. These will not be required or graded, but will help keep students active and working on their skills.

For students in Composition II, we will continue to work online so that you will receive college credit. Make sure your paper that was due today is in by Sunday and I will post something this weekend about the next thing we will be working on. They are allowing us to continue with Google Classroom, so that is much easier.

Any parents who want extra resources, please let us know. We will all be posting and trying to stay in contact as much as possible. All emails will be answered within 24 hours and some of us will post our phone numbers so you can message us that way also.

Please spread the word to anyone who may not have facebook or may not have follow this page or my page. Thank you!!

#wearewmu #wmucsd #wolvespride

post_text:
WMUCSD has 2 feeding sites. PICK UP ONLY at the back door of school Monday-Friday 8am-10 am. Mt Union Church 9am-10am Monday-Friday.

WMUCSD is willing to deliver meals to students/kids on Winfield bus routes. This will be to kids with no transport or access to get to our feeding sites. If you would like a meal delivered please contact Tracie Hartman 319.931.8446, or click on the Meal Request Form at the bottom of this post to get signed up. We will start delivering Monday 3/23. We will start at 8am. We will not get out of the vehicle and will expect someone to come out and get it. Each bag contains a breakfast and a lunch.

If you want on the delivery list, we will need to know how many children need a bag when you contact us. Reminder only 1 bag per child. We are feeding children ages 1-18.
Please respond either way by Thursday, March 19th at 5PM.

Click this link to go to the Meal Request Form: https://forms.gle/NoSHVAkKgfEwzKSs8

Families of K-5 students,

Please visit the school website wmucsd.org to find instructional items from your child's grade level teacher. These items are intended to require little assistance from an adult caretaker. These items are also optional and will not be graded. They are intended to help review content that has already been instructed and reduce learning loss that tends to happen over vacation (like summer) or school closure (like for COVID-19) periods.

Thanks,

WMU Staff

WMU Ag Ed & Crooked Creek FFA
February 12 at 2:45 PM ¬∑

We were approved! Mrs. Brown applied for a grant from the Iowa Agriculture Literacy Foundation to help cover the costs of materials for going to elementary classes (PK-5) and sharing about agriculture.

Different grade levels will have different activities the high school agriculture & FFA students will be taking to their rooms in the upcoming month(s). Be on the lookout for future posts about the activities in the elementary rooms as we try to work them into schedules that work for everyone! We are excited to share agriculture with the younger students at WMU!

shared_text:
WMU Ag Ed & Crooked Creek FFA
February 12 at 2:25 PM ¬∑

Yesterday was a day of trying something new for the Intro to Agriculture class too! There was struggling with remembering flower parts...so, we tried out a flower lab.

Students were given a cup with materials that had everything they needed (Mrs. Brown did a sample first to make sure they had enough supplies but hid hers away from students' eyes.) A list of parts was listed on the board and a sketch of a flower by Mrs. Brown to jog their memory. From there, students had to use their materials and list of terms on the board to create a flower, once they got it correct (flowers had to be labeled correctly OR they had to explain to Mrs. Brown the flower parts in their flower) they could eat their flower and the extra ingredients. #wmucsd

On Tuesday, January 14th, the WMU students will be discussing and sharing their J term projects with the public from 11:00-2:00. Please feel free to come visit, watch, ask questions, etc...

Thank you to all who have donated supplies, money, and other things to help make this great. Special thanks to the WMU PTO, Pilot Grove Savings Bank, and the Mt Pleasant Walmart Distribution Center.

#wearewmu #wmucsd #wolvespride

post_text: This is Isaac Bender doing something good at recess. During recess today there was something spilled in the tunnel so no kids could play in it. He cleaned it up so his friends could then use it. He earned a wolf ticket for good friendship and working hard. Way to go Isaac!!
